# 📊 Healthcare Substance Use & Opioid Harm Analytics During COVID-19

## 🔍 Overview  
This project analyzes the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on substance-related harms across Canada using healthcare data published by the Canadian Institute for Health Information (CIHI).

The analysis focuses on trends in:
- Emergency Department (ED) visits  
- Hospitalizations  
- Opioid poisonings  
- Alcohol-related harms  
- Substance-related deaths  
- Demographic and income-based disparities  

Using Python and Power BI, this project transforms public healthcare reporting data into an interactive analytics solution designed to support healthcare monitoring, public health reporting, and decision-making.

The project is inspired by CIHI’s report *Unintended Consequences of COVID-19: Impact on Harms Caused by Substance Use*.

---

# 🎯 Business Problem  
During the COVID-19 pandemic, Canada experienced rising substance-related harms alongside major disruptions to healthcare access and public health services.  

Healthcare organizations and public health agencies require timely analytics to:
- monitor substance-related healthcare burden,
- identify high-risk populations,
- track opioid-related harms,
- understand healthcare utilization trends,
- and support data-driven public health decisions.

This project aims to provide an interactive healthcare analytics dashboard that helps stakeholders monitor trends in substance-related harms and identify areas requiring intervention and resource planning.

---

# ❓ Key Business Questions  
- Which substance-related harms increased most during COVID-19?  
- How did ED visits and hospitalizations change during the pandemic?  
- Which populations experienced the highest increases in harm?  
- How did opioid poisonings evolve over time?  
- Did substance-related cases become more severe during the pandemic?  
- Which demographic and income groups were most affected?  
- How can healthcare leaders monitor emerging public health risks more effectively?  

---

# 📂 Dataset  
The dataset is based on publicly available healthcare reporting data released by CIHI related to:
- Emergency Department visits
- Inpatient hospitalizations
- Opioid poisonings
- Substance-related deaths
- Demographic and income-level trends
- Healthcare severity levels during COVID-19

The analysis compares trends between:
- March–September 2019
- March–September 2020

---

# 🛠️ Tools & Technologies  

| Tool | Purpose |
|---|---|
| Python | Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA), trend analysis, KPI calculations |
| Pandas & NumPy | Data manipulation and analysis |
| Matplotlib | Data visualization and trend exploration |
| Power BI | Interactive dashboard development and KPI reporting |
| DAX | KPI measures and analytical calculations |

---

# 📊 Dashboard Features

The Power BI dashboard includes:

- KPI cards for ED visits, hospitalizations, opioid-related deaths, and substance-related deaths
- Monthly trend analysis (2019 vs 2020)
- Substance-level comparisons across ED visits and hospitalizations
- Age-based analysis of substance-related harms
- Income quintile analysis
- Mortality and severity indicators
- Interactive filtering by substance type

### Intended Audience
- Healthcare Executives  
- Public Health Leaders  
- Policy Analysts  

---

# 📊 Key Insights

- Substance-related ED visits decreased by 5% between March–September 2020 compared with the same period in 2019.
- Substance-related hospitalizations increased by 5% despite reductions in overall healthcare utilization.
- Substance-related deaths increased by 12%.
- Opioid-related deaths increased by 23%.
- Alcohol remained the most reported substance across ED visits and hospitalizations.
- Lower-income populations experienced a disproportionate burden of substance-related harms.
- Young adults (20–39) accounted for a large share of substance-related healthcare utilization. 

